76561198361121740,Recommended,252250,30011410,Posted: 18 February,all,laurajoannemartin,"If you like god games, hard sci-fi, hyper-realistic sims, and dark, British humour, then you'll like Maia.I've played Maia for about 20 hours now, more than enough to have built myself a fully self-sustaining colony with all the bells and whistles, including the rooms that require certain levels of research, so I've seen pretty much all of the permutataions of gameplay you can get within the game.It took me a while to get that Maia is a delicate balance between active user input (build orders, smelting stuff, etc) and watching the formidable AI systems run. However, once I understood this, my colony ran a lot better, was more productive, and I got a lot more out of gameplay. Another challenge is balancing the amount of activity. Unlike other sims, your colonists get tired and sick and dehydrated if you work them too hard, so you can't just set 4892438 build orders and go make some tea. On that note, I LOVE the level of detail - from temperatures reactive to whether an air vent system is on or off, to body heat of chickens altering room temperatures, to the relative humidity being affected by water condensing systems, to atmosphere quality being augmented by potted plants, to plants *literally* getting species-specific diseases like fungal rot and black spot... there is phenomenal detail in here that I struggle to understand at the best of times, but massively appreciate.Another thing is that dev Roth is quite literally the King of the Easter Egg. Most people probably don't notice or read the descriptions and names of objects, but there are some real 'laugh out loud' examples of punning names that play very well within the cultural nexus of dry, dark British humour. There's also a brilliant sense of British understatement to the emails - instead of saying 'we're literally starving here, half-wit, build some food prep stations', they say wonderfully passive aggressive things like ""I hope this lack of X isn't another bureaucratic oversight."" Ah, the art of the strongly worded letter is strong in this game.In terms of practical playability, the game is pretty easy to get the hang of; controls are intuitive, and the 'tabbing through' range of objects based on context rather than having to go through a sims-style full-scale menu system is great.The fact that the game is still under development shouldn't put you off - it's fully fledged already, and the updates (like 0.60 adding colonist relationships... again, how the heck was this coded in?!) just add more levels of detail and interest to an already fully formed and extremely well-thought-out idea. I paid full price for the game and don't mind as it's an indie dev, but it seems like it has frequent sales, so definitely pick this up right now.Overall 9/10, definitely reccommend."
,Not Recommended,252250,23135562,"Posted: 22 May, 2016",all,Lilin,"The game that never gets finished.2 and a half years ago it was released as extremely early access pre-alpha on steam, since then it has hardly improved at all and is not even remotely close to being finshed or playable.Today the game still has many of the same bugs and issues it did when it was released and is still in a barely playable state.The developer is still working on the game, but at the pace it is going and considering how inexperienced and inefficient the developer still is after all these years, it seems the game will still take another 2-3 years to finish.Because the idea behind this game is rather interesting and refreshing, and there aren't a whole lot of alternatives, it may be worth checking in on this game again in another 2-3 years. Then again, by then there might be something much better.So for now, do not buy, not even on sale. It's not even remotely worth it at the moment."
